Assessing the Impact of Code Samples Evolution on Developers' Doubts

Abstract. To accelerate the learning process of technical resources by developers, code samples have been provided and maintained by organizations, such as Amazon, Google, and Microsoft. Code samples are special software projects made available in public repositories with the main goal of teaching developers how to use features of frameworks, libraries, or other technical resources. Since code samples are software projects themselves, they evolve over time. However, if changes do not preserve essential characteristics such as size and simplicity throughout evolution, code samples may lose their usefulness. In this work, we investigate how code samples evolve and how evolution may impact on developers questions. We conduct an exploratory study on the evolution of 159 code samples provided by Android, AWS, Azure, and Spring Boot, assessing metrics related to size and complexity as well as developers questions about the analyzed code samples in Stack Overflow. We observed that organizations may not be paying due attention to the key characteristics of code samples during evolution. Our analysis also indicates that changes in some of these characteristics are related to an increase in questions about code samples.

Projects: 159
Commits: 12,120
Stack Overflow Questions: 1,297
Time window: 2013 - 2020

In the following sections we present all steps for the conduct of this experiment.

1 - Getting Questions

The first step was search for Stack Overflow questions about code samples. We consider a question about code samples, questions with code sample url in your body. We have a list of code samples used from previus study and available in 1-GettingQuestions/listOfSamples. To look for each questions in Stack Overflow and check it body, we used Stack Exchange database available in https://ia800107.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/27/items/stackexchange/stackoverflow.com-Posts.7z. Because we were interested in code sample with question, we exclude all of them without it. The script used in that step is available in 1-GettingQuestions/Script.ipynb. After the execution of this steps we got a list of code samples with questions and a list of these questions with your creation date:

2 - Extrating Metrics

Now we have a list of code samples with your questions and we need to extract the metrics: Physical Lines (PL), Line of Code (LOC), Commented Line (CLOC), Readability, Java Files, Classes, Weighted Methods per Class (WMC), Depth of Inheritante Tree (DIT), Number of Children (NOC), Colpling Between Objects (CBO), Response for a Class (RFC), Lack of Cohesion in Methods (LCOM). For all these metrics only Readability is not extract from SciTools Understand, it is extract with .jar provided by Buse and Weimer and available in 2-ExtractingMetrics/readability.jar. For SciTools Understand use, we needed to download (https://www.scitools.com/free-trial) and install inside 2-ExtractingMetrics/understand. After installing, we needed to insert a registration key for all funcionalities. After install all tools, we needed to download all code sample repositories from github, this process is avaiable in 2-ExtractingMetrics/1-DownloadingCodeSamples.ipynb. For metric extract we use 2-ExtractingMetrics/2-ExtractingMetrics.ipynb, in that one each commit is assessed for each code sample. Note that, we perform the extraction by project but some metrics by file, so we needed to aggregate all files into one value. For that we extract the metrics using the median and average, and after that decide which one choose. The following table shows a example of output for code smaples android-testing from Android. The results for all code samples are available in 2-ExtractingMetrics/metrics.

3 - Data Aggregation

This step have two goals: first join the code sample commits by month (looking for commit date), this means summarize all commits of a month into one by average of metrics. For example, if a code sample has 3 commits in January 2018 and for each commit LOC has 4, 9, 8. So we change these 3 commits into one by average of metrics, in this case LOC value is 7. This approach is performed for all code samples individually. After that, the second step is joint these results with the Stack Overflow questions. Finally we have metrics and questions sorted by month, then we perform data normalization for next steps. The results and scripts are available in 3-DataMerge/1-CodeSampleAgregation. 4 - Statistical Tests

For that we used Mann-Kendall test available in https://pypi.org/project/pymannkendall/. We ran this test for all code samples and the script is available in 4-StatisticalTests/1-CodeSample. Now we want to know if exists correlation between metrics behavior and Stack Overflow questions. For that we use 3 tests: first to identify if the metric has normal distribution (Shapiro-Wilk Test). If the metric has normal distribution we perform Pearson Test otherwise we apply Spearman test. Scripts for this step is available in 4-StatisticalTests/1-CodeSample/1-StatisticalTests.ipynb.
